1.Introduction to Graphs
-->A Graph is a non-linear data structure consisting of a collection of:
   Vertices (Nodes),Edges (Connections)
Graphs are used to represent relationships between objects.
Unlike a tree, graphs have no rules — nodes can connect freely, in any direction, with or without cycles.

2.Why Graphs? — Limitation of Trees Trees are great for hierarchical data (folders, family trees),
but they are too restrictive for many real-world problems: 
• A node in a tree can have only ONE parent. 
• There is only ONE path between any two nodes.
• There are NO cycles in a tree. Graphs remove all these restrictions. 
Any node can connect to any other node, in any direction, with any number of connections. 
Important rule:  Every Tree is a Graph, but every Graph is NOT a Tree.
Every tree is a graph   ✓        Every graph is not a tree   ✗ 

-->Real World Examples
Google Maps
Cities  -> Vertices
Roads   -> Edges
Social Network
Users       -> Vertices
Friendship  -> Edges
Computer Network
Devices     -> Vertices
Connections -> Edges

