6. Breadth First Search (BFS)
BFS explores all nodes at the current level before going deeper. Think of it as exploring a
building floor by floor — finish all rooms on floor 1 before going to floor 2.
How BFS Works
                    0
                /       \
            1               2
        /
    3


Starting from node 0, BFS step by step:
 Step          Queue (front -> back)       Visited                         Output
 Start         [0]                         {0}                             —
 Pop 0         [1, 2]                      {0, 1, 2}                       0
 Pop 1         [2, 3]                      {0, 1, 2, 3}                    1
 Pop 2         [3]                         {0, 1, 2, 3}                    2
 Pop 3         []                          {0, 1, 2, 3}                    3

Output: 0     1      2   3
BFS Template Code
 from collections import deque
def bfs(start):
     q = deque([start])                # initialize queue with start node
     visited = set([start])            # mark start as visited IMMEDIATELY
         while q:
             node = q.popleft()        # take from FRONT (FIFO order)
             print(node)               # process node
             for nei in graph[node]:
                 if nei not in visited:
                     visited.add(nei)       # mark BEFORE adding to queue
                     q.append(nei)          # add to BACK of queue

 bfs(0)

Property                                Value
 Data Structure                          Queue (collections.deque)
 Time Complexity                         O(V + E)
 Space Complexity                        O(V)
 Key Advantage                           Finds the SHORTEST PATH in unweighted graphs
 Common Uses                             Shortest path, level-order traversal, nearest neighbour


